  "prompt": "How can you determine the ionic charge of sodium?",
  "response": "To determine the ionic charge of sodium (Na), you should consider its position in the periodic table and its electron configuration.\n\n1. **Position in the Periodic Table**: Sodium is located in Group 1 (also known as alkali metals) of the periodic table. Elements in this group typically have one valence electron.\n\n2. **Electron Configuration**: Sodium has an atomic number of 11, which means it has 11 protons and 11 electrons when it is in its neutral state. The electron configuration for sodium is:\n   - 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b9. \n\nThe outermost shell (3s) contains one electron. Atoms tend to achieve a stable electron configuration similar to the nearest noble gas. For sodium, the nearest noble gas is neon, which has an electron configuration of 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076.\n\nTo achieve stability, sodium will lose its one valence electron from the 3s orbital:\n\nNa \u2192 Na\u207a + e\u207b\n\nBy losing one electron, sodium becomes positively charged, with a resulting ionic charge of +1. Thus, the ionic charge of sodium is typically +1.",
